# --- RSVP (production) — Supabase Edge only (no Apps Script URL / webhook in the browser repo) ---
# 1) Create a GCP service account, enable Sheets API, download JSON.
# 2) Share your spreadsheet with the service account email (Editor).
# 3) Supabase Dashboard → Edge Functions → submit-rsvp → Secrets:
#    GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON=<paste full JSON string>
#    RSVP_SPREADSHEET_ID=<from sheet URL>
#    RSVP_SHEET_TAB_NAME=RSVPs   (optional)
# 4) Link CLI (optional): supabase link --project-ref <Reference ID>
# 5) Deploy Edge function: npm run deploy:submit-rsvp
#    Requires SUPABASE_PROJECT_REF in .env (same as Reference ID) and `supabase login`.
#    (supabase/config.toml has verify_jwt = false for anonymous guests.)
# 6) Expose anon keys for GitHub Actions (repo → Settings → Secrets and variables):
#    Secrets: SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN (Account → Access Tokens, starts with sbp_),
#             VITE_SUPABASE_URL, VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY,
#             optional SUPABASE_PROJECT_REF (or put Reference ID as a Variable instead)
#    Pushing updates under supabase/functions/submit-rsvp/ triggers workflow
#    "Deploy submit-rsvp (Supabase Edge)" when token + ref are configured.
#
# Local: fill .env → npm run rsvp:check → npm run supabase:sync-ref → supabase login → npm run deploy:submit-rsvp
#
# Optional (one-shot): add SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN=sbp_... to .env, then `gh auth login` and
# `npm run github:env:publish` to push VITE_* + project ref (+ token) into GitHub.
# Remove sbp_* from .env afterward if you don’t want it on disk.
#
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://YOUR_PROJECT.supabase.co
VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=eyJ...anon...

# Dashboard → Project Settings → General → Reference ID
SUPABASE_PROJECT_REF=YOUR_PROJECT_REF

# Legacy Google Apps Script + Vite proxy (optional local only — not wired in UI anymore):
# VITE_RSVP_SCRIPT_URL=
# VITE_RSVP_WEBHOOK_SECRET=
